# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acc-women-s-premier-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/2014-acc-elite-league] The first tournament of second division of ACC Premier League was held in Singapore between 7–13 June 2014.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/2014-acc-elite-league] Singapore won the tournament and qualified for 2016 ACC Premier League.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/2014-acc-elite-league] Saudi Arabia finishing second qualified for 2015 ICC World Cricket League Division Six.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] The **2024 ACC Women's Premier Cup** was the inaugural edition of the ACC Women's Premier Cup, hosted by Malaysia in February 2024.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] The tournament was a part of the qualification pathway for 2024 Women's Twenty20 Asia Cup.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] The Asian Cricket Council announced the complete fixtures for the tournament on 16 January 2024.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] Four semi-finalists Malaysia, Nepal, Thailand and United Arab Emirates qualified for the 2024 Women's Twenty20 Asia Cup, after it had been originally announced that only the finalists (UAE and Malaysia) would qualify.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] UAE defeated Malaysia in the final by 37 runs.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] Ahead of the tournament, Malaysia and Kuwait contested a three-match T20I series.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] Updated to match(es) played on 13 February 2024.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/2026-acc-women-s-premier-cup] The **2026 ACC Women's Premier Cup** was the second edition of the ACC Women's Premier Cup, and was hosted by Malaysia in June 2026.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/2026-acc-women-s-premier-cup] The tournament was a part of the qualification pathway for 2026 Women's Twenty20 Asia Cup.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-championship] The **ACC Championship** was a cancelled two-day cricket tournament run by the Asian Cricket Council that is contested between its members nations.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-championship] The first tournament was scheduled to be held in December 2014.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-championship] It was canceled due to the busy preparation schedules of Afghanistan and UAE for the 2015 ICC Cricket World Cup.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-championship] The 2014 ACC Championship was scheduled to be the first tournament of the ACC Championship, to be held in the United Arab Emirates on 7–14 December 2014.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-championship] The top four teams from the 2014 ACC Premier League, Afghanistan, UAE, Nepal and Oman had qualified for the championship.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-championship] Due to the busy preparation schedules of Afghanistan and UAE for 2015 ICC Cricket World Cup, the tournament was cancelled.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] The **ACC Fast Track Countries Tournament** was a three-day cricket tournament run by the Asian Cricket Council (ACC), contested between its top-ranking ICC associate members.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] It was played three times between 2004 and 2006, and then replaced by the ACC Twenty20 Cup.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] Some matches in the second edition of the tournament held first-class status, as they were simultaneously ICC Intercontinental Cup matches.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] Hong Kong, the UAE and Nepal all qualified for the 2005 ICC Intercontinental Cup as a result of their top three finish in the tournament.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] A separate final was originally set to be held, but as Hong Kong and the UAE topped the group with only their group match to take place, it was decided to make the final group match the overall tournament final.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] The UAE beat Hong Kong by five wickets in that final.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-fast-track-countries-tournament] Matches in this tournament between Hong Kong, Nepal and the UAE also counted towards the 2005 ICC Intercontinental Cup.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-men-s-challenger-cup] The **ACC Men's Challenger Cup** is a Limited-overs (50 overs) and T20 International cricket tournament run by the Asian Cricket Council and contested in a league system by associate members of ACC.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-men-s-challenger-cup] This is a part of the qualification pathway towards the ACC Premier Cup and the Asia Cup.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-men-s-challenger-cup] On 9 February 2023, the ACC announced the schedule of the inaugural tournament, with 8 teams taking part (the host Thailand, Bahrain, Bhutan, Saudi Arabia, Indonesia, Maldives, Iran and Myanmar).
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] The **ACC Premier Cup,** officially known as the **ACC Men's Premier Cup** is a men's limited-overs international cricket tournament organized by the Asian Cricket Council and contested in a league system by the associate members of ACC.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] It crowns the best associate team in Asia and also serves as the final qualification pathway towards the Asia Cup.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] It evolved from the former ACC Trophy Elite cricket competition.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] The inaugural edition of the tournament took place in April and May, 2023 with Nepal as the host.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] Currently, It's the top tier tournament for associate teams in Asia.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] This is a cricket tournament evolved from the former ACC Trophy, contested in 50 overs format and also the ACC Twenty20 Cup in T20 format, both were organized by the Asian Cricket Council.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] ACC Trophy was replaced by ACC Premier League in 2014.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] ACC Premier League was held in Malaysia between 1–7 May 2014.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] The top four teams, Afghanistan, UAE, Nepal and Oman qualified for the 2014 ACC Championship, which was cancelled.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] After first edition of the tournament in 2014 and ACC Twenty20 Cup in 2015, the ACC reformed the tournament structure into a regional, rather than divisional basis.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] In 2023, ACC reinvented the tournament and divided the associate members in a two-tier league system.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] **Premier Cup** is the top tier tournament while Challenger Cup being the bottom tier.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] It's played in both 50-overs and T20I format alternatively, serving as a single ultimate prize for associate teams in Asia.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-premier-cup] Additionally, the tournament resembles the format used in Asia Cup, as it serves as a qualification path for the same.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-women-s-premier-cup] The **ACC Women's Premier Cup** is a limited-overs international cricket tournament organized by the Asian Cricket Council (ACC).
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-women-s-premier-cup] It is contested by the women's national teams of the associate members of ACC.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-women-s-premier-cup] It is part of the qualification pathway for the Women's Asia Cup.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-women-s-premier-cup] The inaugural tournament was held in February 2024 with Malaysia as the host.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-women-s-premier-cup] It was contested by sixteen teams, with Indonesia and Japan entering the tournament as invitees from the East Asia-Pacific region.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-women-s-premier-cup] In 2023, ACC released the 2023-24 calendar of events, where the beginning of the tournament was revealed.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-women-s-premier-cup] Initially, a women's Challenger Cup was also a part of a two-tier qualification pathway for the Asia Cup.
[src:acc-women-s-premier-cup/acc-women-s-premier-cup] But in January 2024, a new calendar was released with only a 16-team women's Premier Cup.
